    slug: 'thailand-budget-travel-guide',
    title: 'Thailand on a Budget: How to Travel Well for £30–£50/Day',
    excerpt: 'Thailand can be done incredibly cheaply without sacrificing comfort or experiences. Here\'s a realistic breakdown of costs and how to keep them low.',
    content: `<h2>Is Thailand Still a Budget Destination?</h2><p>Thailand has become more expensive over the past decade, but it remains one of the best-value travel destinations in Asia. With careful planning, you can travel comfortably for £30–50/day — or splash out on luxury for what budget accommodation costs in London.</p><h2>Accommodation: £8–£40/night</h2><ul><li>Backpacker dorm: £5–10</li><li>Private guesthouse room: £15–25</li><li>Boutique hotel: £30–60</li><li>4-star resort: £60–150</li></ul><h2>Food: £5–£20/day</h2><p>Eat street food and local restaurants to spend £5–8/day on three meals. A curry and rice from a local shop costs 50–80 baht (£1–£1.80). Western restaurants and hotel dining cost 3–5x more.</p><h2>Transport: £2–£15/day</h2><p>BTS/MRT in Bangkok: 16–59 baht per trip. Songthaew (shared pickup): 10–50 baht. Inter-city bus: 100–300 baht. Private transfers: 1,200–3,000 baht for airport-to-hotel.</p><h2>Activities: £5–£40/day</h2><p>Temple entrance fees: free to 500 baht. Muay Thai fight: 400–1,000 baht. Scuba diving day trip: 1,800–2,500 baht. Thai massage: 250–500 baht/hour.</p><h2>Sample Daily Budget</h2><ul><li>Street food breakfast + lunch + dinner: 150 baht</li><li>BTS/transport: 60 baht</li><li>One major attraction: 300 baht</li><li>Accommodation (guesthouse): 600 baht</li><li>Drinks/snacks: 100 baht</li><li><strong>Total: ~1,210 baht (~£27)</strong></li></ul>`,
