    slug: 'thailand-national-parks-guide',
    title: 'Best National Parks in Thailand for Nature Lovers',
    excerpt: 'Thailand has 157 national parks covering 19% of the country. These are the most spectacular ones for wildlife, trekking, and natural scenery.',
    content: `<h2>Thailand's Protected Nature</h2><p>Thailand's national park system protects some of Southeast Asia's most biodiverse landscapes — from the cloud forests of the north to the coral reefs of the Andaman Sea. With 157 national parks, there's more wild Thailand than most visitors realise.</p><h2>Khao Yai National Park</h2><p>UNESCO World Heritage Site, 2 hours from Bangkok. Home to Asian elephants, gibbons, Siamese firebacks, and hornbills. The 2,165 sq km park has well-marked trails and night safari tours. Best visited October–May.</p><h2>Doi Inthanon National Park</h2><p>Chiang Mai province. Home to Thailand's highest peak (2,565m). Twin royal pagodas, stunning waterfalls, and excellent birdwatching. Often cold at the summit in winter — bring layers.</p><h2>Erawan National Park</h2><p>Kanchanaburi province, 3 hours from Bangkok. The seven-tiered emerald waterfall is one of Thailand's most beautiful natural features. Swim in the clear pools between tiers. Can be crowded on weekends.</p><h2>Similan Islands Marine National Park</h2><p>Nine islands in the Andaman Sea, rated among the world's top 10 dive sites. Exceptional visibility, whale sharks, manta rays, and pristine coral. Open November–April only.</p><h2>Kaeng Krachan National Park</h2><p>Thailand's largest national park, near Hua Hin. Very good for wildlife spotting — elephants, Asiatic black bears, leopards, and over 400 bird species.</p>`,
