    slug: 'thailand-transport-complete-guide',
    title: 'Getting Around Thailand: Complete Transport Guide 2025',
    excerpt: 'From Bangkok\'s BTS to overnight trains and private transfers — here\'s every way to get around Thailand, with honest advice on which to use when.',
    content: `<h2>The Key Transport Options</h2><p>Thailand has a well-developed transport network, but choosing the right option for each journey can be confusing. Here's a practical breakdown of every method and when to use it.</p><h2>Bangkok Public Transport</h2><ul><li><strong>BTS Skytrain:</strong> The best way to get around central Bangkok. Fast, air-conditioned, 16–59 baht per trip. Covers Sukhumvit, Silom, and Chatuchak.</li><li><strong>MRT (Metro):</strong> Complements the BTS. Good for Lumphini, Chatuchak, and Rattanakosin areas.</li><li><strong>Chao Phraya Express Boat:</strong> Tourist and local boats along the river. 15 baht (orange flag) to 60 baht (tourist boat). Great for accessing riverside temples.</li><li><strong>Metered Taxi:</strong> Cheaper than ride-hailing for short distances. Always insist on the meter.</li><li><strong>Grab:</strong> Thailand's equivalent of Uber. Fixed price, no negotiation, clean cars.</li></ul><h2>Inter-City Transport</h2><ul><li><strong>Domestic Flights:</strong> Bangkok to Phuket or Chiang Mai: £10–30. Book through Thai Airways, AirAsia, Nok Air, Lion Air.</li><li><strong>Overnight Trains:</strong> Bangkok to Chiang Mai (sleeper): 600–1,400 baht. Comfortable, scenic, saves accommodation cost. Book at Hua Lamphong Station or online.</li><li><strong>Intercity Bus:</strong> Cheap and reliable. Bangkok to Phuket: 600–900 baht (10 hours). Bangkok to Chiang Mai: 500–800 baht (9 hours).</li><li><strong>Private Transfer:</strong> Best for shorter distances (up to 4 hours). Door-to-door, flexible timing, no stops. Werest covers major routes across Thailand.</li></ul><h2>Island Transport</h2><p>Ferries connect the mainland to major islands. High-speed boats are faster but rougher — choose based on weather conditions. Car ferries are available to larger islands (Koh Samui, Koh Chang).</p>`,
